1
00:00:00,006 --> 00:00:09,486
When creating demos, switching between
terminal and browser used to lose all your
terminal state. Let me show you how
persistent sessions fix this.

2
00:00:21,945 --> 00:00:24,417
Now switching to browser.

3
00:00:27,405 --> 00:00:32,301
Back to terminal. Watch - the state is
preserved.

4
00:00:37,269 --> 00:00:41,085
Directory and environment variables are
intact!

5
00:00:41,095 --> 00:00:46,087
Now for named sessions - running server
and client terminals simultaneously.

6
00:01:01,899 --> 00:01:05,211
Server running on port twelve thousand
one.

7
00:01:05,521 --> 00:01:07,921
Let's see it in the browser.

8
00:01:12,012 --> 00:01:14,724
The page loads from our server.

9
00:01:14,563 --> 00:01:17,539
Now from a separate client terminal:

10
00:01:21,839 --> 00:01:24,743
Client fetches the same content.

11
00:01:25,160 --> 00:01:29,288
Back to the server terminal - we can see
the request logs.

12
00:01:31,603 --> 00:01:35,131
And our original terminal still has its
state.

13
00:01:42,771 --> 00:01:47,619
That's persistent sessions and named
sessions - complex demos made simple.

